.TH MINIOS-SESSION-MANAGER 1 "August 2025" "MiniOS" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
minios-session-manager \- graphical interface for managing MiniOS persistent sessions
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B minios-session-manager
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B minios-session-manager
provides a GTK3 graphical user interface for managing MiniOS persistent sessions.
It offers an intuitive way to browse, create, activate, and delete sessions without using the command line.
.PP
The application internally uses
.BR minios-session-cli (1)
to perform actual session operations, providing a user-friendly frontend to the command-line functionality.
.SH FEATURES
The graphical interface provides the following capabilities:
.TP
.B Session List View
Displays all available sessions in a sortable table with columns for ID, status, mode, version, edition, size, and last modification time.
.TP
.B Current Session Display
Shows information about the currently active session at the top of the window.
.TP
.B Session Creation
Create new sessions with a choice of persistence modes (native, dynfilefs, raw) through a dialog interface. The interface automatically detects filesystem compatibility and shows only supported modes.
.TP
.B Session Activation
Activate any available session to make it the default for the next boot.
.TP
.B Session Deletion
Delete selected sessions with confirmation dialogs. The currently active session cannot be deleted.
.TP
.B Cleanup Operations
Remove old sessions based on age threshold with configurable number of days.
.TP
.B Filesystem Compatibility
Automatic detection of media filesystem type with restrictions on incompatible session modes. Size limitations are enforced for FAT32 raw images.
.TP
.B Compatibility Warnings
Automatic detection and warnings for sessions created with different MiniOS versions or editions.
.SH INTERFACE ELEMENTS
.TP
.B Main Window
The main window displays the session list, current session information, and action buttons.
.TP
.B Refresh Button
Updates the session list and current session information.
.TP
.B Create Session Button
Opens a dialog to create a new session with mode selection.
.TP
.B Activate Session Button
Activates the selected session after confirmation.
.TP
.B Delete Session Button
Deletes the selected session after confirmation (if not currently active).
.TP
.B Cleanup Sessions Button
Opens a dialog to clean up old sessions with configurable age threshold.
.TP
.B About Button
Shows application information and version details.
.SH SESSION MODES
The application supports creation of sessions in three different modes:
.TP
.B Native Mode
For POSIX-compatible filesystems (ext4, btrfs, etc.). Most efficient option.
.TP
.B DynFileFS Mode
For non-POSIX filesystems (FAT32, NTFS). Uses expandable container files.
.TP
.B Raw Mode
For any filesystem. Uses fixed-size image files.
.SH DIALOGS
.TP
.B Create Session Dialog
Allows selection of session mode and provides information about each mode's characteristics and requirements. Automatically detects filesystem type and shows only compatible modes. Includes size selection for dynfilefs and raw modes with filesystem-specific limitations.
.TP
.B Activation Confirmation
Confirms session activation and warns about potential compatibility issues.
.TP
.B Deletion Confirmation
Confirms session deletion with warnings about irreversibility.
.TP
.B Cleanup Configuration
Allows setting the age threshold for automatic cleanup of old sessions.
.TP
.B Error and Information Dialogs
Display operation results, errors, and informational messages.
.SH KEYBOARD SHORTCUTS
.TP
.B F5
Refresh session list
.TP
.B Delete
Delete selected session (with confirmation)
.TP
.B Ctrl+N
Create new session
.TP
.B Ctrl+Q
Quit application
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
.B minios-session-manager
Launch the graphical session manager.
.TP
Application Menu → System → MiniOS Session Manager
Launch from the desktop application menu.
.SH FILES
.TP
.B /usr/share/applications/minios-session-manager.desktop
Desktop entry file for application menu integration.
.TP
.B /usr/share/polkit-1/actions/dev.minios.session-manager.policy
PolicyKit configuration for administrative operations.
.SH DEPENDENCIES
.TP
.B minios-session-cli
The command-line utility that performs actual session operations.
.TP
.B GTK3
Graphical toolkit for the user interface.
.TP
.B Python3
Python interpreter and GTK bindings.
.SH EXIT STATUS
The application runs until closed by the user. Individual operations may succeed or fail with appropriate user feedback through dialog boxes.
.SH NOTES
.PP
The graphical interface requires a running X11 or Wayland session. For headless or text-only systems, use
.BR minios-session-cli (1)
instead.
.PP
The application starts without requiring root privileges and automatically requests authentication via PolicyKit when needed. Write operations (create, activate, delete sessions) will show authentication dialogs when system permissions require it.
.SH PRIVILEGE ESCALATION
The graphical interface handles privilege escalation transparently:
.TP
.B Session Viewing
Reading session information typically requires no authentication.
.TP
.B Session Management
Creating, activating, or deleting sessions automatically triggers authentication prompts via PolicyKit when needed.
.TP
.B Error Handling
Clear error messages are displayed when authentication fails or is cancelled by the user.
